==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: caesura
<hw>cae*su"ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E.
<plw>caesuras</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, L. <plw>C⟦ae⟧sur⟦ae⟧</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr></plu> <ety>[L. <ets>caesura</ets> a cutting off, a
division, stop, fr. <ets>caedere</ets>, <ets>caesum</ets>, to cut off.
See <er>Concise</er>.]</ety> <def>A metrical break in a verse, occurring
in the middle of a foot and commonly near the middle of the verse; a
sense pause in the middle of a foot. Also, a long syllable on which the
c⟦ae⟧sural accent rests, or which is used as a foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ In the following line the <xex>c⟦ae⟧sura</xex> is
between <xex>study</xex> and <xex>of</xex>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prop | er stud | y \'d8 of | mankind | is man.</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a pause or interruption (as in a conversation);
<as>as, after an ominous <ex>caesura</ex> the preacher
continued</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

